        {
          "number": 7,
          "slidetitle": "Validating AI Before Full Deployment",
          "subtitle": "Steps to test before going live",
          "slidecontent": "• Run the AI output against a small, low-risk pilot project first\n• Check results manually\n• Compare AI-generated designs with proven, human-verified benchmarks\n• Involve a qualified engineer or domain expert to review outputs before sign-off\n• Document every discrepancy found during testing, no matter how minor\n• Only scale up once the tool has passed consistent, repeatable checks",
          "do_not_include": false
        },
        {
          "number": 8,
          "slidetitle": "Key Points to Remember",
          "subtitle": "Core principles for safer AI design",
          "slidecontent": "• Always validate AI-generated designs against real-world engineering standards before use\n• Human review is non-negotiable\n• Treat AI output as a starting point, not a finished solution\n• Document every change made to an AI-generated blueprint so decisions stay traceable\n• Involve domain experts early, especially when safety is a factor\n• As a next step, audit one recent AI-assisted project using a structured validation checklist",
          "do_not_include": false
        }
      ],
      "scripts": [
        {
          "number": 1,
          "script": "Welcome to this course on Generative Design Tools, where we'll be exploring the balance between innovation and safety. So, what exactly are generative design tools? Put simply, they are AI-powered systems that can automatically produce design blueprints, layouts, and structural plans, often within minutes. Rather than a designer sitting down and manually drafting every detail, the software does a huge amount of that work for you. These tools are being used across architecture, engineering, and product development, and they are becoming increasingly popular with teams who are under real pressure to deliver results quickly. And it is easy to see why, because instead of spending days on a single concept, you can generate hundreds of design variations in a very short space of time. But here is the important point we will keep coming back to throughout this course: speed does not automatically mean safe. Just because a tool can produce something quickly, that does not mean the outcome is reliable or fit for purpose.",
          "do_not_include": false
        },
        {
          "number": 2,
          "script": "Generative design tools are genuinely impressive. They can produce complex blueprints and detailed outputs far faster than any human team could manage, and on the surface, that looks like a huge win. But here is where we need to pause and look a little more carefully. Buried inside those AI-generated files, there can be errors that simply are not visible at first glance. They are easy to miss, especially when a deadline is looming and the temptation is to skip the validation steps and just move forward. Speed starts to feel like progress, and that feeling can be deceptive. Because a design that looks polished and complete is not automatically a safe one. The risks do not announce themselves. They sit quietly beneath the surface, and if we are not deliberately looking for them, we can miss them entirely. That is exactly what this lesson is going to help you understand and address.",
          "do_not_include": true
        },
        {
          "number": 3,
          "script": "So, let's talk about why human oversight is absolutely critical when we're working with AI-generated blueprints. AI can produce designs that look perfectly convincing on screen, but contain subtle errors that are very easy to miss if nobody is checking carefully. Some of those errors could actually put a design in breach of building regulations or safety codes, which is a serious problem. This is where experienced human professionals become invaluable, because they bring contextual knowledge and real-world judgement that AI simply doesn't have. They can spot mistakes that the software wouldn't flag, things like a design that technically works in isolation but doesn't suit the specific environment or use case. Catching those issues early matters enormously, because the further a flawed design travels through the process, the more expensive it becomes to correct. And ultimately, we're not just talking about money here. Poor validation can put people's lives at risk, which is why this step is non-negotiable.",
          "do_not_include": false
        },
        {
          "number": 4,
          "script": "You've got a shiny AI-generated design in front of you. It looks impressive, it's detailed, and the tool produced it with complete confidence. But here's the thing: that confidence doesn't mean it's correct. Generative AI tools can produce outputs that appear polished and thorough, while quietly containing errors buried deep within the complexity. And because the output looks so complete, those mistakes are easy to miss if you're not actively looking for them. This is exactly why validation isn't a choice. Running proper checks and verification processes is how you catch critical flaws before they become serious problems. It's also worth remembering that all the usual safety standards and regulations still apply, regardless of how the design was produced. The AI doesn't know your compliance requirements, and it certainly isn't accountable for them. You are. A qualified human being needs to review and sign off on any AI-generated output before it goes anywhere near implementation.",
          "do_not_include": false
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "script": "So, we've seen how powerful these generative design tools can be, but here's something really important to understand: AI can make mistakes, and those mistakes aren't always obvious. A generated blueprint might look perfectly reasonable on screen, yet still violate local building regulations or safety standards. That's why human oversight isn't optional, it's essential. As a designer or engineer, you bring something the AI simply doesn't have, and that's contextual understanding. You know the project, the site, the client's needs, and the regulatory environment. You're able to spot something that looks technically correct but is actually completely wrong for the situation. And catching those errors early matters enormously, because fixing a problem at the review stage costs a fraction of what it costs to correct it further down the line. So please, treat AI output as a starting point, not a finished product. Always review and validate before you approve anything for production or submission.",
          "do_not_include": true
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "script": "So, AI-generated designs can look incredibly convincing, but that doesn't mean they're always correct. These tools can produce outputs that contain subtle errors, things that aren't immediately obvious just from looking at the screen. That's why having a trained human review the work is absolutely essential. An experienced engineer or designer will spot the kinds of critical flaws that an AI simply won't flag itself, whether that's a structural weakness, a material incompatibility, or something that just wouldn't work in the real world. And before anything gets built or manufactured, you must test and validate the design thoroughly. This isn't just good practice, it's often a legal requirement. Industry standards and regulations in most sectors specifically require a qualified professional to sign off on designs before they move forward. Ultimately, this is about more than compliance. When designs are used in products or structures that people rely on, proper validation is what keeps people safe.",
          "do_not_include": true
        },
        {
          "number": 7,
          "script": "Before you roll out any AI design tool across a live project, you really want to put it through its paces first. Start small. Pick a low-risk pilot project and run the AI outputs through it, then check those results manually rather than just trusting them at face value. Compare what the AI produces against designs you already know are sound, ones that have been verified by experienced professionals. And speaking of professionals, make sure a qualified engineer or domain expert actually reviews the outputs before anything gets signed off. This is not a step to skip. Crucially, keep a record of every discrepancy you spot during testing, even the ones that seem trivial, because small anomalies can point to bigger underlying issues. Only once the tool is producing consistent, repeatable results should you think about scaling up. Validation is not a bureaucratic box-ticking exercise; it is genuinely how you protect your project and your reputation.",
          "do_not_include": false
        },
        {
          "number": 8,
          "script": "So let us bring everything together with a few core principles to carry forward. Whatever AI tool you are using, always check its output against recognised engineering standards before you act on it. Human review is not optional, it is essential. Think of what the AI produces as a first draft, something to build on rather than a finished answer. As you refine that draft, keep a clear record of every change you make, because traceability matters enormously when safety is involved. And do not wait until the end of a project to bring in your domain experts. Get them involved early, particularly where lives or critical systems are at stake. Now, for your next practical step, I would encourage you to take one recent AI-assisted project and run it through a structured validation checklist. That single exercise will sharpen your instincts and help you spot where the process can be strengthened. These habits, built consistently, are what separate responsible AI use from risky shortcuts.",
          "do_not_include": false
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
